data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 10 (EF Core 10), the Cosmos DB provider let you **opt in** to sync-over-async via a warning configuration. In **.NET 11 (EF Core 11), that opt-in is removed entirely**. Synchronous LINQ operators against the Cosmos provider now **unconditionally throw `InvalidOperationException`** — there is no workaround.

All four of your methods are affected:

| Sync (throws) | Async replacement |
|---|---|
| `ToList()` | `ToListAsync()` |
| `First(…)` | `FirstAsync(…)` |
| `Count()` | `CountAsync()` |
| `SaveChanges()` | `SaveChangesAsync()` |

### Migration

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Why**: The underlying Azure Cosmos DB SDK v3 is async-only. The sync path was always just doing `.GetAwaiter().GetResult()` internally, risking threadpool starvation and deadlocks. The temporary opt-in was provided to give teams migration time — that grace period is now over.

You'll also need to propagate `async`/`await` up through your controllers/services that call these methods.
